If nothing changes, where will you be 5 years from now?

It’s a hard question—but an important one.

The good news?

One decision can be the catalyst for everything else.

I started my coaching practice over 6 years ago, and it started with one decision.

I decided to hand in my resignation.

This was no easy feat!

After all, I had worked with most of these people for over ten years. We found solutions together. We dined together. We knew each other’s families…how could I leave them?

Moreover, leaving the financial security of corporate life required a lot of faith, because there was no safety net.

If I failed, I would land right on my butt!

But what if I hadn’t decided to bet on myself? 💡

Where would I be five years later?

I can only speculate, but I think my speculations are close to accurate:

👉🏽I would have still been an Administrative Assistant. I would have missed out on partnering with some phenomenal people to help them achieve their incredible dreams, because I would have still been sitting behind a desk, booking lunch dates, screening phone calls, filing expense reports, and playing a bit character in someone else’s dream.

👉🏽I would have missed out on writing my first book and being featured in magazines and podcasts. No one would have had the chance to hear and apply my theories on: creating a lifestyle that fulfills you, the necessary steps to take before setting goals, or how to reimagine how you show up in this world.

👉🏽I would still be living the lifestyle that I help others escape. Chasing promotions that never come, fitting my life into someone else’s box, dimming my light so others would find me palatable, and showing up inauthentically to maintain some sense of safety.

That one decision helped me evolve in ways I never imagined!

Look, I can promise you this, if you don’t decide to do something different...

We'll be having the same conversation, five years from now.

However, one phone call could open up a world you never imagined.

What makes C-Luma different from C-Firma? C for yourself!

Think of C-Luma as C-Firma’s gentler cousin. C-Luma contains two milder, less acidic forms of vitamin C at a lower strength (10.0%). The formula includes hydration-boosting ingredients and has a unique, lightweight water-serum texture. If C-Firma is too strong for you, you may enjoy C-Luma.

Like C-Firma, C-Luma will help improve hyperpigmentation and signs of aging, just at a more gradual pace, while also addressing unique skin concerns like redness and breakouts. C-Luma can be used alongside any of our actives and even used twice daily (morning and night!). 

You can alternate them, too! Try using C-Firma in the morning and C-Luma at night for even greater results.

Give skin what it needs and nothing else! The concept of listening to your skin may sometimes get overcomplicated. Here is the thing—listening to your skin and giving it what it needs is really about being aware of your skin behaviors. 
 
Tightness, excessive oiliness, dryness/flaking, congestion, irritation—these are all behaviors that are signals sent by your skin in response to factors such as environment, the products you’re using, or changes in your personal health.

To reset skin to its happiest, healthiest state, we recommend taking a #drunkbreak. 

During a #drunkbreak, we avoid the #suspicious6 (essential oils, drying alcohols, silicones, chemical sunscreens, fragrances/ dyes, and SLS). These are six categories of ingredients, which, research has shown, can be at the root of common skin issues, such as sensitivity and breakouts.

Beam come true! C-Luma contains a unique blend of 10% vitamin C (9% sodium ascorbyl phosphate and 1% ascorbyl glucoside) to fade the look of hyperpigmentation and post-breakout marks, reduce blemishes, and hydrate instantly.

Sweet Pitti deodorant cream eliminates odor-causing bacteria while absorbing excess moisture from the skin. Our founder, Tiffany Masterson, applies it by putting it in the palm of her hand and massaging it into her armpits (this is also a great opportunity to check for lumps!).

While many deodorants use baking soda, Sweet Pitti does not. Baking soda can be sensitizing, and repeated exposure can disrupt our skin's healthy pH, actually causing more bacteria and odor. Instead, we use mandelic acid because it’s an effective and gentle antibacterial that won’t disrupt the acid mantle of our underarms.

What we leave out of our products is just as important as what we put in, so you will never find what we call the Suspicious 6 (essential oils, drying alcohols, silicones, chemical sunscreens, fragrances/dyes, and SLS) in our line. They’re nothing to be scared of—just be aware. We avoid these six categories of ingredients, which, research has shown, can be at the root of common skin issues, such as sensitivity and breakouts. Once you remove them, skin can reset to its happiest, healthiest state.

The book is an homage to the synthetic glamour of Los Angeles, the cinema of the quotidian. These photographs were shot entirely at the Chateau Marmont on Sunset Boulevard. A Very Bad Man opens with a “rejection letter” from the publisher who commissioned me to make this book.  I turned it into something else completely:
“As I write this, my city is glowing. While usually it glimmers with unparalleled sunlight, it is currently illuminated by seven simultaneous fires. While my city burns, I am in my newly adopted home in Paris, reflecting on this farewell letter of a book dedicated to the illusory town that raised me.
This collection of photographs is an homage to the synthetic glamour of Los Angeles.
Becoming the cinema of the quotidian, it is a backdrop for an existence of your own making.
Sometimes it feels like the end of the Earth, like the edge of ideation, a place that has historically
welcomed new thinkers. One is not surrendering to the weight of history, because she is blessed
with a short-term memory that can only recall what was recorded for those to fantasize about later.
You can be whoever you want to be in LA, an incubator for your wildest dreams.
These photographs were shot entirely at the Chateau Marmont on Sunset Blvd. A historic container for one’s subconscious mind, it needs no introduction.
Most of the characters are my friends, creative by nature, many of which have spent countless moments engaging in the hotel’s delicate tension between discretion and public life. Additionally, I asked nine of my favorite LA fine artists to create works on the hotel stationary inspired by the city.
Insomuch as the same part of your brain processes dreams likewise internalizes the immersive
experience of a film, I think memories from the Chateau live there too.
The main character of these scenes is that special daylight. David Lynch felt lucky to live
with that light; “It thrilled my soul.” Mine too.
With love,
Amanda

I got off the plane in Paro, Bhutan and upon first glance of the massive portrait of His Majesty the King’s family portrait, I knew I was in a mystical place.  The epic beauty of this airport which reads more like a temple was just an introduction to an entire country’s emphasis on material beauty signifying devotion to God. 

And after a decade of dreaming of this perfect country whose spirituality is at the forefront of its existence, I was so excited to visit the parliamentary Zhongs which are always 3/4 monastery, where government officials work alongside monks.  To meet the team and learn about the upcoming Gelephu Mindfullness City @gmcbhutan , where @kingjigmekhesar 
is planning a futuristic city where ethical capitalism can co-exist with nature. 

I even found some equanimous perfection in a monk answering his cell phone in the middle of my blessing ceremony or even people making tik tok’s at the temple. The serenity of a country without billboards, traffic lights, or noise pollution made me realize the chaos we have all become accustomed to.  And on the flipside humanity cannot live without its transgressions.  You can go through religious ceremony repeatedly but still be devoid of spiritual grace.  So grateful for this heart mind and soul opening experience!  Thank you BHUTAN
I love wearing beautiful jewelry as much as I love shooting it !! Thank you @cartier @pirriewright
Had the most fun running around the city with Maya for @christianlouboutinbeauty !

*My Nephew NICOLAI*
I spent this fall day walking around my beloved hometown with my nephew, taking photos with my Hasselblad. 
We are an eyewear family.  When my father left his toy business after fleeing Iran in the late 70’s, he came to LA where an acquaintance was in the eyewear business. That world raised us.  One day I would be in his office putting glasses in bags, the next day Ol’ Dirty Bastard was in my living room modeling for my brother’s line while I was wearing the kid’s collection.  All I have is love for my family and the city that took us in.  You can be whoever you want to be in LA.
